        <p>Single-parent meal time is a unique challenge — you're cooking for a small number of people, often with limited time, sometimes with picky eaters, and no one to hand anything off to. The goal isn't gourmet. The goal is fed, reasonably healthy, and not a crisis every night.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The one shift that changes everything:</strong> stop thinking meal by meal and start thinking in batches. Cook once, eat three times. It's not glamorous but it's the system that actually works.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The batch cooking approach</h2>
        <p>Pick one day a week (Sunday is common, but whatever works) and spend 60–90 minutes cooking components rather than complete meals. Components are flexible — a cooked protein, a grain, a roasted vegetable — and mix-and-match into different meals through the week.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>A big batch of ground beef or chicken</strong> → tacos Monday, rice bowls Wednesday, pasta sauce Friday</li>
          <li><strong>A pot of rice or quinoa</strong> → side dish, fried rice, burrito bowls</li>
          <li><strong>Roasted vegetables</strong> → side dish, added to eggs, thrown into pasta</li>
          <li><strong>Hard-boiled eggs</strong> → breakfast, snack, added to salads</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The mental load reduction alone is worth it — you make decisions once instead of every night.</p>

        <h2>Weeknight meals that actually happen</h2>
        <p>These take 20–30 minutes, use common ingredients, and kids generally eat them:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sheet pan dinners</strong> — protein + vegetables on one pan, 25 minutes at 400°F. Almost no cleanup. Endlessly variable.</li>
          <li><strong>Stir fry</strong> — frozen vegetables, protein, soy sauce, over rice. 15 minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Quesadillas</strong> — cheese is non-negotiable, add whatever else is available. Kids eat them every time.</li>
          <li><strong>Pasta with jarred sauce + protein</strong> — not a recipe, a fallback. Keep pasta and a few jars in the pantry always.</li>
          <li><strong>Egg scrambles</strong> — eggs, whatever vegetables are around, cheese. Works for dinner. Kids accept it.</li>
          <li><strong>Slow cooker / instant pot meals</strong> — set in the morning, done when you get home. Chili, pulled chicken, soups. Worth learning three or four recipes.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Grocery shopping without wasting money</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Shop with a list built from a loose meal plan.</strong> Even a rough idea of five dinners cuts impulse spending significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Store brands for staples.</strong> Pasta, canned tomatoes, rice, frozen vegetables, canned beans — store brand is identical at 20–30% less.</li>
          <li><strong>Frozen vegetables are fine.</strong> Nutritionally comparable to fresh, cheaper, and don't go bad before you use them.</li>
          <li><strong>Buy proteins in bulk and freeze.</strong> Chicken thighs, ground beef, and pork shoulder are among the cheapest proteins and freeze well. Thaw in the fridge overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>Eggs are your best friend.</strong> Cheap, fast, high-protein, kids eat them. Keep two dozen on hand at all times.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Dealing with picky eaters</h2>
        <p>A few things that actually help:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Separate components, same meal.</strong> If your kid hates mixed food, serve the protein, starch, and vegetable separately rather than combined. Same cooking, less battle.</li>
          <li><strong>One safe food per meal.</strong> Always include something you know they'll eat. They don't have to eat everything, but they eat something.</li>
          <li><strong>Involve them in picking and prepping.</strong> Kids who helped choose or make the food are more likely to eat it. Let them pick between two options, not from an open menu.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid short-order cooking.</strong> One meal, served to everyone. They eat what's served or they don't eat. This is hard initially and gets easier.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Keeping the kitchen stocked</h2>
        <p>With these on hand, you can always make something:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Pasta + jarred sauce</li>
          <li>Canned beans and canned tomatoes</li>
          <li>Frozen vegetables</li>
          <li>Eggs</li>
          <li>Chicken thighs (frozen) and ground beef (frozen)</li>
          <li>Rice or another grain</li>
          <li>Olive oil, butter, salt, garlic powder, a few spices you actually use</li>
          <li>Cheese (shredded, in a bag — it lasts and goes on everything)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Good enough is good enough.</strong> A nutritionally complete, reasonably balanced meal that you can actually make on a Wednesday night beats a perfect meal you don't have the energy to cook. Don't let perfect be the enemy of fed.</p>
        </div>

        <p>If budget is a pressure point right now, the <a href="{{ '/financial/assistance/' | url }}">Assistance Programs guide</a> covers SNAP and WIC — both significantly reduce grocery costs for families who qualify.</p>
